<div id="voice" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">01</span>His own voice</h2>
  <p>Most of what the disenchanted world knows about shamanism it knows secondhand — through scholars, travelers, and collectors who described practitioners they were not. Davi Kopenawa is the practitioner. Born around 1956 near the Rio Toototobi, he is a Yanomami shaman and the Portuguese-speaking spokesperson for the Yanomami people in Brazil, and his cosmology, his life, and his case against the people destroying his forest reach us in <em>The Falling Sky: Words of a Yanomami Shaman</em> — told to and composed with the French anthropologist Bruce Albert (<em>La Chute du ciel</em>, 2010; English, Harvard University Press, 2013).</p>
  <p>The distinction matters to this book. The page that follows tries to do something the book is otherwise careful about: stay inside what he has said, and not fill the rest in.</p>
</div>
<div id="xapiri" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">02</span>The xapiri and the forest</h2>
  <p>At the center of Yanomami cosmology are the <em>xapiri</em> — the shaman spirits Kopenawa works with. <em>The Falling Sky</em> is at once autobiography, ethnography, and cosmology, and it does not separate these the way a Western account would. The knowledge of the forest, the work of the shaman, and the defense of the land are one thing told in one voice.</p>
  <p>This is the part most easily lost when someone else does the telling. Rendered from outside, the spirits become belief, the forest becomes resource, and the shaman becomes informant. Told from inside, they are not separable at all — which is exactly why the book matters here in his words rather than in a summary of them.</p>
</div>
<div id="miners" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">03</span>The miners and the falling sky</h2>
  <p>Kopenawa has spent decades campaigning to expel illegal gold miners — <em>garimpeiros</em> — and rubber tappers from Yanomami land. He co-founded the Hutukara Yanomami Association in 2004; following his international campaigning, Brazil officially recognized Yanomami land in 1992; he and Hutukara received the Right Livelihood Award in 2019. The work has drawn death threats.</p>
  <p>The book's title is his image, not a metaphor borrowed for it. In Yanomami cosmology the destruction the whites work through their extraction threatens to bring the sky down. What the disenchanted call ecological collapse, the shaman names from his own vantage as the falling sky — the same event, seen from inside the cosmology that the mining is destroying.</p>
</div>
<div id="appropriation" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">04</span>Why his voice, and not a scholar's</h2>
  <p>Elsewhere this book draws on a scholar of shamanism, Mircea Eliade, and is honest that his account carries its own baggage. Kopenawa answers a problem that account cannot. The most common way the enchanted world reaches the disenchanted one is as a thing studied — described, classified, and spoken for by people standing outside it. That posture is itself a small enclosure: it takes the authority to say what a practice means and keeps it on the outside.</p>
  <div class="callout"><span class="callout-label">The appropriation problem</span><p>The land-defender material in this book risks romanticizing the people it admires — admiring them, that is, in someone else's words. Kopenawa is the corrective. He is not an example of a shaman defending the forest that a writer assembled; he is a shaman defending the forest who set down the account himself. The voice is the point. To put a summary in its place would be to do, in miniature, the thing the chapter is against.</p></div>
</div>
<div id="commons" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">05</span>A commons defended in its own words</h2>
  <p>A forest the Yanomami govern, held against miners who would convert it to extraction, is a land commons under enclosure — the same structure this book traces from the Narmada valley to Standing Rock. What Kopenawa adds is that the defense is not only of the land but of the standing to speak for it. The miners take the forest. The long habit of the disenchanted world takes the account of the forest. He refuses both.</p>
  <div class="callout"><span class="callout-label">For the commons</span><p>The commons is governed by those who live in it, and entered by many doors. A defense of the commons that lets outsiders narrate it has already conceded part of what it claims to protect. Kopenawa holds both at once: the forest and the right to say what the forest is. The book places him here not as a subject of study but as a voice — and asks the reader to go to <em>The Falling Sky</em> for the rest, where it belongs.</p></div>
</div>
